            <div class="post-prose">

                <p class="text-xl leading-relaxed text-gray-600 mb-10 italic border-l-4 border-medicalTeal pl-6">If you have been researching non-surgical hair loss treatments, you have probably come across two popular options — PRP (Platelet-Rich Plasma) therapy and mesotherapy. Both involve scalp injections, both promise to reduce hair fall and boost regrowth, and both are offered at nearly every aesthetic clinic. So which is better, PRP or mesotherapy? The answer is not as simple as picking one over the other. Your ideal treatment depends on the cause of your hair loss, how advanced it is, and what your body responds to best. In this detailed guide, we break down every aspect of both treatments so you can make an informed decision.</p>

                <h2>Understanding PRP Therapy for Hair</h2>

                <p>PRP, or Platelet-Rich Plasma therapy, is a regenerative treatment that uses your own blood to stimulate hair growth. A small sample of blood is drawn from your arm, placed in a centrifuge to separate the platelet-rich plasma from other blood components, and then injected directly into the areas of thinning on your scalp. If you want a deeper dive into how it works, read our complete guide on <a href="what-is-prp.php">what PRP is and how it helps hair growth</a>.</p>

                <p>The science behind PRP is straightforward. Platelets contain growth factors — proteins that play a critical role in tissue healing and cell regeneration. When concentrated and injected into the scalp, these growth factors wake up dormant hair follicles, increase blood supply to the follicle, and extend the active growth phase (anagen phase) of the hair cycle. The result is thicker, stronger hair and reduced shedding over time.</p>

                <p>PRP has gained significant credibility in the dermatology community because it uses autologous material, meaning it comes from your own body. This virtually eliminates the risk of allergic reactions or rejection, making it one of the safest hair restoration procedures available today.</p>

                <h2>Understanding Mesotherapy for Hair</h2>

                <p>Mesotherapy is a technique that involves injecting a customized cocktail of vitamins, minerals, amino acids, enzymes, and sometimes medications directly into the mesoderm — the middle layer of skin on the scalp. Unlike PRP, which relies on your body's own healing mechanisms, mesotherapy delivers external nutrients and pharmaceutical agents straight to the hair follicles.</p>

                <p>The specific ingredients in a mesotherapy cocktail vary depending on the clinic and the patient's needs, but common components include biotin, zinc, copper peptides, hyaluronic acid, minoxidil, finasteride, and various B-complex vitamins. This targeted delivery system ensures that the follicles receive a concentrated dose of exactly what they need, bypassing the digestive system and bloodstream where nutrients can be diluted or lost.</p>

                <p>Mesotherapy has been used in aesthetic medicine for decades, originally developed in France in the 1950s for pain management before being adapted for hair loss treatment and skin rejuvenation.</p>

                <h2>Detailed Comparison: PRP vs Mesotherapy</h2>

                <h3>Mechanism of Action</h3>

                <p><strong>PRP</strong> works from the inside out. It triggers your body's natural repair processes by flooding the scalp with concentrated growth factors including PDGF (Platelet-Derived Growth Factor), VEGF (Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor), and TGF (Transforming Growth Factor). These proteins stimulate stem cells within the hair follicle, promote new blood vessel formation around follicles, and encourage the transition from the resting phase to the growth phase.</p>

                <p><strong>Mesotherapy</strong> works through direct nutrient supplementation. It addresses deficiencies at the follicular level by delivering vitamins and minerals that may be lacking due to poor diet, stress, or medical conditions. Some mesotherapy formulations also include DHT blockers that can help combat androgenetic alopecia (pattern baldness) at a local level.</p>

                <h3>Ingredients and Components</h3>

                <p><strong>PRP</strong> contains only your own blood components — specifically, a concentrated form of platelets suspended in plasma. There are no synthetic additives, drugs, or external substances involved. The quality of your PRP depends on your own health, platelet count, and the preparation method used.</p>

                <p><strong>Mesotherapy</strong> uses a tailored blend of external compounds. A typical formulation may include B vitamins (B5, B6, B7, B12), zinc, iron, copper, amino acids like cysteine and methionine, coenzymes, vasodilators, and sometimes prescription medications like minoxidil or dutasteride. The cocktail can be customized to address your specific type of hair loss.</p>

                <h3>The Procedure</h3>

                <p><strong>PRP procedure:</strong> The session begins with a blood draw (about 10-20 ml). The blood is processed in a centrifuge for 10-15 minutes to isolate the platelet-rich plasma. A topical numbing cream is applied to the scalp, and the PRP is then injected using fine needles across the treatment area. The entire process takes approximately 45 to 60 minutes.</p>

                <p><strong>Mesotherapy procedure:</strong> No blood draw is needed. After applying topical anaesthesia, the pre-mixed nutrient solution is injected into the scalp using a mesotherapy gun or fine needles at shallow depths (1-4 mm). Sessions are typically quicker, lasting 20 to 40 minutes depending on the size of the treatment area.</p>

                <h3>Cost Comparison</h3>

                <p>In Gurgaon, a single PRP session at a reputable clinic generally costs between INR 4,000 and INR 10,000, depending on the preparation method and the expertise of the practitioner. Mesotherapy sessions tend to be more affordable, ranging from INR 2,500 to INR 7,000 per session.</p>

                <p>However, mesotherapy often requires more total sessions than PRP, which can balance out the overall cost. A standard PRP protocol involves 3-4 initial sessions, while mesotherapy may require 4-6 sessions. When you factor in maintenance treatments over a year, the total expenditure can be comparable for both.</p>

